  "prompt": "What's the definition of vote margin?",
  "response": "The vote margin refers to the **difference in the number of votes between the winning candidate or option and the runner-up candidate or option in an election or vote.**\n\nIn simpler terms, it's how much the winner beat the loser by.\n\nFor example:\n\n*   If Candidate A gets 55% of the vote and Candidate B gets 45%, the vote margin is 10% (55% - 45%).\n*   If Option X receives 100,000 votes and Option Y receives 80,000 votes, the vote margin is 20,000 votes (100,000 - 80,000).\n\nThe vote margin is often expressed as a percentage, but it can also be expressed as the absolute number of votes.  A large vote margin indicates a decisive victory, while a small vote margin indicates a close race.\n",
